<HEADLINE>
1,200 TO PLAY HUQIN TO MARK CENTER'S 20TH ANNIVERSARY
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  March 14 (CNA) 03/14/07  18:40:28 (By Y.L. Kao)
</P>
<P>
Around 1,200 people are slated to take part in an event April  28
as part of the 20th anniversary celebrations of the National
Chiang Kai-shek Cultural Center, which comprises the National
Theater and the National Concert Hall in the Chiang Kai-shek
Memorial Hall Complex in downtown Taipei, event organizers said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The event, to be organized by the Chai Found Music Workshop at
the plaza of the complex, is designed to challenge the Guinness
World Record for the largest number of people simultaneously
playing the huqin, a Chinese string instrument, according to the
organizers.
</P>
<P>
The organizers said the concert will feature two classic huqin
pieces -- "lia ng hsiao" and "sai ma" -- and called on all those
interested in taking part to apply before April 15.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 200 people have registered for the event,
including 10-plus Japanese.
</P>
<P>
The organizers will offer free instructions for prospective
participants.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the performance, around 20 other musical works
rearranged by contemporary composers will be played, with the aim
of presenting a fascinating blend of pop music and classical
pieces and bringing new inspiration to music lovers, the
organizers added.
</P>
